INTRODUCTION¶

The dataset is the trip data of Ford GoBike, a regional public bicycle sharing system that covered the California's San Francisco Bay Area, one of the largest bike-sharing system in the US.

This is an exploration and analysis of a dataset containing Ford GoBike's trip data covering the period from 28 June 2017 to 30 April 2019.

Data can be downloaded here and data description is provided here .

2) DATA ASSESSMENT¶

I will be assessing my data both visually and programmatically for quality and tidyness.¶

Quality

Data that has issues with data content.

  • Missing data
  • Duplicate data
  • Invalid data
  • Inaccurate data.

Tidyness

Data that has issues with its structure, like rows, columns and table.

  • Each Variable forms a column
  • Each Obserevation forms a row
  • Each type of observational unit forms a table

Data Assesssment Dimensions

  • COMPLETENESS - Missing data.

  • VALIDITY - Conformation of data to pre-established schema.

  • ACCURACY - Appropriateness of data even though it conforms to schema.

  • CONSISITENCY - Representation of data to a standard format.

Observation¶

Quality

  1. There are some entries that don't have any details on start station and end station - Completeness

  2. There are some entries that don't have any response on whether they use bike share for all their rides or not- Completeness

  3. The duration of the trips are in seconds, they should be in minutes for better analysis- Accuracy

  4. The start_time and end_time columns are not in datetime format- Consisitency

  5. To make exploraton and detection of relationships easy, the user type column will be better as a dummy variable rather than categorical. - Accuracy

  6. To make exploration and detection of relationships easy, there should also be a dummy column that shows whether a particular trip day is weekend or weekday. - Accuracy

Tidyness

  1. Since one of my interest is trips by weekends or weekdays, there should be a column to diffrentiate weekends from weekdays.- Accuracy

  2. The location variables ( start_long, end_long, end_lat and start_lat ) should be used to derive ride distance which is needed for insightful analysis.-Accuracy

B) Tidyness Issues¶

Issue #1 : The location variables ( start_long, end_long, end_lat and start_lat ) should be used to derive ride distance which is needed for insightful analysis.¶

Define¶

I'll calculate the distance between start and end station for each trip, and store it in a new column distance; this is calculated using geodesic function included in geopy library.

The geodesic distance is the shortest distance on the surface of an ellipsoidal model of the earth.

Code¶

In [22]:
# I will define the function to make it run through the whole dataset
def distance_calc(start, end):
        distance = geodesic(start, end).km
        return distance
# I will calculate the distance between start and end station
df['distance'] = df.apply(lambda x: distance_calc((x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude']), (x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude'])), axis=1)

DATA ANALYSIS AND EXPLORATION¶

INTRODUCTION¶

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

There are 3,177,717 observations with 9 features

Duration of trip ( in minutes)

Distance covered ( in kilometers)

Start time

End time

Is weekend (dummy variable 1-weekend, 0-not weekend)

Is subscriber (dummy variable 1-subscriber, 0-Customer)

Start station name

End station name

The main features of interest in the dataset.¶

I'm interested in Yearly trend, Monthly trend, Daily trend, Effects of weekends, comparing subscribers and customers, Station performance.

Features in the dataset that will help support my investigation into these features of interest.¶

Duration and Distance are the two features that specifically show the usage of the company.

QUESTIONS¶

In this section of this report, I will state the problem question, describe the questions that I plan on exploring over the course of this report.

The Problem Question¶

Question - How has the company performed overtime and what are the factors influencing the performance?

My Explorative Questions¶

I will be exploring the dataset based on the variables below.

Duration

The distribution of the trip duration.

The correlation of trip duration with trip distance.

The correlation of trip duration with weekends and weekdays.

The correlation of trip duration with subscribers and customers.

Distance

The distribution of trip distance.

The correlation of trip distance with trip duration.

Time Trend analysis

Trips by year

Trips by months

Trips by weekdays.

Trips by hour of days by each user type.

Trips by weekends or weekdays.

Trips by customers or subscribers.

Performance of Stations

Most Popular start stations

Most Popular end stations

Effects of being a subscriber

Correlation of trips by customers and subscribers.

Correlation of trip duration by customers and subscribers.

Time trend analysis by customers or subscribers.

PS : I will be using trip duration as the basis instead of trip distance for my analysis because the trip distance is just the geodesic distance which might not always depict the real distance covered.

# Heatmap for correlations between 'duration','distance, and 'is_weekend' for each user type
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 12,5
# Create a mask for duration <= 30 minutes
duration30 = df['duration'] <= 30
num_cols = ['duration', 'distance', 'is_weekend']
corr_df = df[num_cols][duration30].groupby(df['is_subscriber']).corr()
sns.heatmap(corr_df.unstack(), annot=True, linewidths=1.5)

plt.show()

Total Insights¶

Most trips are within the duration of 3 minutes to 10 minutes.

Most trip distances is in the range of 0.75 to 1.5 kilometers.

The Popular Start Stations and the end Stations are quite similar which might mean that people use bikes to and fro the bike stations.

There was an obvious growth in the patronage of Ford GoBike overtime as the number of trips per month shows a systematic increase overtime.

There are drops in rides in all Novembers and Decembers which needs further investigation.

Trips peak everyday around 8a.m-9a.m and 5p.m-6p.m which can mean that subscribers take bikes to work and take bikes back from work.

Trips are just average around 10a.m to 3p.m and might be best time to move bikes to popular start points that have scarce bikes from popular end points.

There are longer trips during weekends.

There are more trips on workdays than weekends.

Subscribers Patronize more on workdays than weekends.

Customers also patronize more on Fridays and weekends than other days.

There is also a stronger correlation between distance, duration and Subscribers as compared to Customers. This further establishes that for the customers there are longer trips duration which gives a more spread of trip duration and lower correlation.

Though most customers also patronize with the same peaks of 8a.m to 9a.m and 5p.m to 6p.m, customers tend to patronize more around 10a.m to 3p.m relative to subscribers which might mean that customers have a more flexible patronage as expected.

Customer go on longer trip durations than subscribers with the Subscribers trips mostly below 20 minutes while the Customers trips spread modally till about 35 minutes.

It can be suspected that Customers love for long trips and more patronage during weekends is what results in longer trips during weekend.

There is a similar trend in the patronage of both customers and subscribers within a month, Customers just tend to have sharp drops and peaks(flexibility of patronage) while subscribers have smoother drops and peaks( relatively better consisitency)
